expected_response:
Examine the signals for dissemination bias in the review methods, the characteristics of the body of evidence and, if possible, with graphical and statistical approaches.
In particular:
The risk of dissemination bias may be higher for systematic reviews of non-randomized studies than of RCTs;
Studies with small sample sizes or small numbers of events are more likely to remain unpublished or ignored. In areas where large population-based studies are the norm, missing studies are less likely to go unnoticed, as large studies are more difficult to 'hide' than small ones;
The likelihood of missing studies might be less in research fields where study costs are high, and study methods are complex. On the other hand, it seems plausible that easy-to-conduct and less costly studies might be more likely to remain unpublished when their results are deemed negative or unfavourable by the study investigators.
In emerging research fields, dissemination bias is more likely because studies with positive results tend to be published more quickly than those with non-significant outcomes. As a result, systematic reviews conducted early, when only a few initial studies are available, may overestimate the effects of new interventions;
The inclusion and assessment of studies presented as conference abstracts only or disseminated as reports or in grey literature only, might help to assess whether dissemination bias is at play. If studies that are only reported as conference abstracts or in grey literature showed smaller effect estimates than studies that were published in full, this might indicate the presence of dissemination bias.
